From Mark Davis Subject Re Blinking Cursor in Xterm Barry Margolin writes In article Mark Davis writes You are stuck in a distributed system feedback loop What if you are on an Xterminal or running xterm over the net to another machine That is when the load problems If you had a machine with Xterminals attached and they all had blinking cursors in xterm's this could represent a considerable ethernet bandwidth Ethernet certainly has enough bandwidth for a few blinking My Lisp Machine blinks the cursor twice a second and updates the time in the status line every This uses under bytes second or about of the bandwidth of A hundred of them on a single ethernet might be a problem but a couple dozen should be Granted it's nothing to loose sleep over but this is Ethernet's tragic flaw the more activity especially lots of tiny activity the more collisions happen and the performance gets exponentially I am just now opposing ANY kind of waste of bandwidth under Although in a polling system it would not be so Mark Davis Lake Taylor Hospital Norfolk VA Computer Services mark taylor mark